<subSubSection lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="449" pageId="13" pageNumber="448" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="13" pageNumber="448">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1720,2034]" box="[151,1435,1720,1741]" pageId="13" pageNumber="448">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,1720,1741]" pageId="13" pageNumber="448">1. Tergites black........................................................................................ 2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1720,2034]" box="[151,1435,1749,1770]" pageId="13" pageNumber="448">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,1749,1770]" pageId="13" pageNumber="448">- Some tergites reddish partially or completely................................................................ 3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="13" pageNumber="448">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1720,2034]" pageId="13" pageNumber="448">
<keyLead pageId="13" pageNumber="448">
2. Macrosetae of mystax mixed black and white, longer than proboscis length. Ocellar macrosetae mainly black, in length commonly reaching to apex of antenna. Scutum with dense long black and white setae and macrosetae. Scutellum with numerous long white apical scutellar macrosetae and usually with a few long white discal scutellar setae.......... 
<taxonomicName authority="(Loew)" authorityName="Loew" baseAuthorityName="Loew" baseAuthorityYear="1871" box="[1243,1436,1837,1858]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Heteropogon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="448" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="filicornis">
<emphasis box="[1243,1358,1837,1858]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="448">H. filicornis</emphasis>
(Loew)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1720,2034]" pageId="13" pageNumber="448">
<keyLead pageId="13" pageNumber="448">
- Mystacal setae and macrosetae mainly black. Mystax equal or shorter than length of proboscis. Ocellar setae white, equal or longer than length of scape and pedicel combined. Scutum with sparse short white and black setae. Postpronotal lobe without setae. Scutellum lacking apical scutellar macrosetae and usually lacking discal scutellar setae......... 
<taxonomicName authority="Sаkhvon &amp; Lelej, 2018" authorityName="Sаkhvon &amp; Lelej" authorityYear="2018" box="[1236,1347,1925,1946]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Heteropogon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="448" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hiemalis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1236,1347,1925,1946]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="448">H. hiemalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1353,1430,1925,1947]" pageId="13" pageNumber="448" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1353,1430,1925,1947]" pageId="13" pageNumber="448">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="449" pageId="13" pageNumber="448">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1720,2034]" box="[151,1435,1955,1976]" pageId="13" pageNumber="448">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,1955,1976]" pageId="13" pageNumber="448">3. Mid tibia with a tuft of black setae in the middle............................................................. 4</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1720,2034]" box="[151,1435,1984,2005]" pageId="13" pageNumber="448">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,1984,2005]" pageId="13" pageNumber="448">- Mid tibia lacking a tuft of black setae in the middle........................................................... 7</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<footnote box="[151,1435,2013,2034]" pageId="13" pageNumber="448">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1720,2034]" box="[151,1435,2013,2034]" pageId="13" pageNumber="448">4. Pulvillus are well developed and longer than length of half of claw.............................................. 5</paragraph>
</footnote>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,151,700]" box="[151,1436,151,172]" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,151,172]" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
- Pulvillus shorter than length of half of claw................................................. 
<taxonomicName authority="Hermann" authorityName="Hermann" authorityYear="1906" box="[1239,1436,151,172]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Heteropogon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pyrinus">
<emphasis box="[1239,1340,151,172]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">H. pyrinus</emphasis>
Hermann
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,151,700]" box="[151,1435,181,202]" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,181,202]" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">5. Mid tibia with white or pale dense setae not reaching tarsomere I............................................... 6</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,151,700]" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
<keyLead pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
- Mid tibia with white dense setae reaching tarsomere I–II. The tuft of black setae in the middle of mid tibia equal or shorter than length of white setae. Scutum with long dense white setae and macrosetae. Scutellum with few white apical scutellar macrosetae and numerous discal scutellar setae......................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Lehr" authorityName="Lehr" authorityYear="1970" box="[1286,1436,269,290]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Heteropogon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosus">
<emphasis box="[1286,1384,269,290]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">H. pilosus</emphasis>
Lehr
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,151,700]" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
<keyLead pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
6. Mid tibia with white dense setae and with conspicuous tuft of black setae in the middle. Scutum with short white and black setae. Scutellum with 2–4 white apical scutellar macrosetae..................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Loew" authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1851" box="[1249,1430,327,348]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Heteropogon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornatipes">
<emphasis box="[1249,1369,327,348]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">H. ornatipes</emphasis>
Loew
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,151,700]" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
<keyLead pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
- The tuft of black setae in the middle of mid tibia equal to or shorter than length of pale setae. Scutum with dense short black setae. Scutellum with 2–4 (rarely 6) black apical scutellar macrosetae.............................. 
<taxonomicName authority="Loew" authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1847" box="[1249,1435,386,407]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Heteropogon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scoparius">
<emphasis box="[1249,1374,386,407]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">H. scoparius</emphasis>
Loew
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,151,700]" box="[151,1435,415,436]" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,415,436]" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">7. Stylus thin and long.................................................................................... 8</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,151,700]" box="[151,1436,444,466]" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,444,466]" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
- Stylus wide and short, in length (without aristomere) equal to or more than half of postpedicel length....... 
<taxonomicName authority="Sаkhvon &amp; Lelej, 2018" authorityName="Sаkhvon &amp; Lelej" authorityYear="2018" box="[1285,1353,445,466]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Heteropogon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ater" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1285,1353,445,466]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">H. ater</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1359,1436,444,466]" pageId="14" pageNumber="449" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1359,1436,444,466]" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,151,700]" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
<keyLead pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
8. Macrosetae and setae of mystax white, with few dark brown macrosetae in lower facial margin in frontal view. Postocular macrosetae and setae white. Scutum with short sparse white setae, some dark brown. Scutellum lacking apical scutellar macrosetae. Fore tarsi, especially tarsomeres I–IV anterodorsally and posterodorsally with dense, comparably long white setae.......................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Hermann" authorityName="Hermann" authorityYear="1906" box="[1231,1436,562,583]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Heteropogon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lugubris">
<emphasis box="[1231,1340,562,583]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">H. lugubris</emphasis>
Hermann
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,151,700]" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
<keyLead pageId="14" pageNumber="449">
- Mystax with only white macrosetae and setae. Postocular macrosetae white, but setae white and black. Scutum with short sparse black setae, some of them white. Scutellum with 2 long white apical scutellar macrosetae. Fore tarsi, especially tarsomeres I–IV anterodorsally and posterodorsally with white setae comparatively dense and long posterodorsally only.............................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName authority="Lehr" authorityName="Lehr" authorityYear="1970" box="[1232,1436,679,700]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Heteropogon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mesasiaticus">
<emphasis box="[1232,1384,679,700]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="449">H. mesasiaticus</emphasis>
Lehr
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
</subSubSection>
